T1  - Intergenerational and international trade
AU  - Dornbusch, Rudiger
JO  - Journal of International Economics
VL  - 18
IS  - 1
SP  - 123
EP  - 139
PY  - 1985
DA  - 1985/02/01/
SN  - 0022-1996
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0022-1996(85)90008-X
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/002219968590008X
AB  - This paper investigates an economy with one good and a single asset which is a real consol. The term structure of interest rates is established under conditions of perfect foresight. It is shown that in an overlapping generations setting the presence of consols implies a lower level of steady state welfare than would be attainable with an optimal supply of short-term debt. The open economy model maintains the assumption of one good and one real consol and thus focuses on the gains from intertemporal trade. It is shown that opening economies to trade leads to Pareto welfare improvement provided present and all future generations are included in the required compensations. But even if only the current generation participates in compensation, trade may still be welfare improving. Comparative static applications include issue of debt and income growth. Deficit finance leads to increased interest rates and anticipated future deficits affect the term structure of interest. It is shown that increased current income must benefit the country where income grows but will also unambiguously lower steady state welfare abroad.
ER  - 

