AB  - The assumptions of fixed real wages and mobile capital are relatively innocuous taken singly, but taken together they generate models of international trade with distinctly unconventional characteristics. It is possible for a country to be ‘undersold all round’. Cost reductions in one country can result in an overall reduction of employment in other countries. Across the board tariff protection in a single country may reduce domestic employment. The model is presented first for a simple case, and is then generalized to incorporate many countries, many goods, and many, heterogeneous, produced and traded capital goods.
